04332nam a22006975i 9780271079493DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710794937 a10.1515/97802710794932doi  a(DE-B1597)583869  a(OCoLC)1262307657  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0090002bisacsh04a701.151 aGrant, Kim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAll About Process :bThe Theory and Discourse of Modern Artistic Labor /cKim Grant. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Process as Value -- t1 Conceptualizing the Artist's Labor Prior to the Nineteenth Century -- t2 Art, Craft, and Industrialization -- t3 The Artist's Process from the Academic to the Modern -- t4 New Conceptions of the Artist's Process -- t5 The Artist's Process as a Means of Self- Realization -- t6 The Artist's Process at Mid- Century -- t7 Art and Social Processes -- t8 Process Art -- t9 It's All About the Process -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, many prominent and successful artists have claimed that their primary concern is not the artwork they produce but the artistic process itself. In this volume, Kim Grant analyzes this idea and traces its historical roots, showing how changing concepts of artistic process have played a dominant role in the development of modern and contemporary art.This astute account of the ways in which process has been understood and addressed examines canonical artists such as Monet, Cézanne, Matisse, and De Kooning, as well as philosophers and art theorists such as Henri Focillon, R. G. Collingwood, and John Dewey. Placing "process art" within a larger historical context, Grant looks at the changing relations of the artist's labor to traditional craftsmanship and industrial production, the status of art as a commodity, the increasing importance of the body and materiality in art making, and the nature and significance of the artist's role in modern society. In doing so, she shows how process is an intrinsic part of aesthetic theory that connects to important contemporary debates about work, craft, and labor.Comprehensive and insightful, this synthetic study of process in modern and contemporary art reveals how artists' explicit engagement with the concept fits into a broader narrative of the significance of art in the industrial and postindustrial world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt, Modern. 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079493zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271079493.jpg  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK